Braintree Blue: Make address country map to alpha2The (undocumented) standard for the :country key in addresses isnfor it to be the standard two-character code for the country.nThe old behavior for Braintree Blue gateway, fixed in this commit,nwas to take that field and map it to :country_name in Braintree,nwhich generally didn't work as expected.nnNow the gateway puts :country into the :country_code_alpha2 field,nand also allows passing :country_code_alpha2, :country_code_alpha3,nand :country_code_numeric if more control is needed.n

GB is the alpha2 country code for the UKRecently we changed all uses of GB to UK in the code, but this isnactually incorrect, as UK is not the correct country code for thenUK (though it is reserved). I'm retaining UK in the README (as itnis more widely used) but all references in the code should alwaysnbe to GB.n

2checkout integration: Add autosettle supportThe current branch only supported the 2Checkout Pass Through Productsnparameter set which requires that the seller mark tangible sales asnshipped before they will charge the customer. A new method c_prod methodnwas added to allow support for 2Checkout Third Party Cart Parametersnwhich charge automatically.nnThe default purchase routine URL was changed from the multi-pagencheckout to the more popular single page checkout.nnThe notification took the item_id from the cart_order_id parameternreturned by 2Checkout. On sales using the Pass Through Productsnparameters, 2Checkout does not return this parameter causing this methodnto return nil. The method now falls back to the merchant_order_id whenncart_order_id is not passed back so that both the Third Party Cartnparameters and Pass Through Product Parameters can be used.nnCloses #362.n

Ogone gateway: loosen up signature warningsPreviously, deprecation warnings were being spit out anytime antransaction was run without a signature, and anytime a signaturenstrength less than 512 was used. This was a bit onerous, as it requirednnot just code changes, but configuration changes for all legacy Ogonenaccounts. While Ogone may force all customers to start using signaturesnin the future, in all likelihood they'll just make it the default fornnew accounts (as they do today).nnThis commit does two things. First, it continues to give a deprecationnwarning if no signature is supplied, but allows that warning to benoverridden by simply providing a signature_encryptor of none. Second,nit dispenses with any warning regarding signature strength, since thatnis still fully configurable in the Ogone backend.n

Set up a matrix of gem versions to test againstCurrently, for better or for worse, ActiveMerchant is very dependent onnActiveSupport, and is sensitive to changes in it. The main developmentnGemfile for AM, though, simply allowed the version of ActiveSupport tonfloat, and no CI testing was being done against the versions ofnActiveSupport/Rails that AM should explicitly support. This allowed testnfailures to creep in unnoticed, and when bundler suddenly startednresolving a different version of ActiveSupport when running CI, meantnlots of inexplicable breakage.nnThis changeset outlines an explicit set of Gemfiles for the versions ofnActiveSupport that ActiveMerchant currently claims to support. These arenthen plugged into a Travis matrix, such that each one will be explicitlyntested for compatibility, and regressions in older versions will show upnimmediately. The default Gemfile is set to track Rails 3.2; when 3.2 isnsuperceded, it is expected that the current default would get renamednand a new default introduced to track the latest ActiveSupport.nnTo run tests against a particular Gemfile, you can simply set your localnBUNDLE_GEMFILE environment variable to one of them, i.e.:nn  export BUNDLE_GEMFILE=Gemfile_rails23nnCloses #470n

Mercury: Support card-less capture and refundMercury is first a POS system, and only second does online transactions.nDue to this, the standard get back an authorization you can use to donfuture operations on this transaction flow must be explicitly enabled.nnThis enables that flow by having Mercury return a OneTime token fornevery #authorize and #purchase which is stored in the authorizationnstring and can then be used to do captures and refunds. This also addsnthe amount to the authorization string so that a capture can be runnwithout having to re-specify the amount.nnThis type of one-time tokenization is now the default for Mercurynsince it matches so much better with expected ActiveMerchant semantics.nIf the old behavior is desired, pass `tokenization: false` in thenoptions hash when creating the gateway.n

fixes #770 purchase with card token or card idStripe supports charging a card token or a customer's card.nA card number only be passed with an associated customer.nnBoth methods are documented:nnIf you also pass a customer ID, the card must be the ID of a cardnbelonging to the customer. Otherwise, if you do not pass a customernID, the card you provide must either be a token, like the ones returnednby Stripe.js, or a dictionary containing a user's credit card detailsn- https://stripe.com/docs/api#create_chargennResolved this issue by allowing the api user to pass in flags in thenoptions hash.nna) options[:is_token] :ncharging a card tokennb) options[:is_customer_card_id] :ncharging a customer's card.noptions[:customer] should also be included.nnRequest parameters.na) Charging a card token:ncurl https://api.stripe.com/v1/charges n   -u sk_test_NMgf6M5lzRW3Vp345LJvR6Ua: n   -d amount=208973 n   -d currency=usd n   -d card=tok_2DWWZ7t5sJQZPt n   -d description=Charge for test@example.comnnb) Charging a charging a card id.n{namount: 90707ncurrency: usdncustomer: cus_2IJycssqIpDju6ncard: cc_2IJy79OB3PjOChndescription: Spree Order ID: R252432727-AEWE8QEDnpayment_user_agent: Stripe/v1 ActiveMerchantBindings/1.36.0n}n

Paymill: Fix authorizationsIn May 2013, Paymill added some response codes:nhttps://blog.paymill.com/new-response-codes/nnAnd there's now a way to trigger declines and other errors using theirntest gateway.nnThis commit now accounts for the fact that a decline may have 4XX HTPPnstatus code or it may have a 200 status code.  Success in Paymill meansnthat it's a 200 status code && the response_code within the body isn20000.  Except for the Void operation.  In that case, just a 200nstatus code is sufficient since the body doesn't include anresponse_code.nnThe Purchase operation returns a 4XX for a failure but the Authorizenreturns a 200 for a failure.  Now when an authorize fails on the Paymillnside, Active Merchant once again reports that transaction as havingnfailed.nnThis commit also fills the response with the appropriate responsenmessage based on the response_code since the body doesn't include thentext.  This ActiveMerchant adapter now handles the response descriptionnmapping to give end users a better idea of what went wrong.nnCloses #923.n

Braintree Blue: Allow specifying credit card tokenThis makes it possible to use an explicit card token, rather thannBraintree automatically generating it. If no token is passed itncontinues to be generated automatically.nnAlso exposes the credit card token in the response.n
Braintree Blue: Allow specifying the customer idThis allows specifying a customer id when storing a credit card rathernthan having one generated automatically.n

Braintree Blue: Scrub invalid emails and zipsBraintree is strict with emails and zips, which can cause unexpectednfailures. This simply substitutes nil if a known-bad email or zip isnpassed in so that the transaction doesn't fail due to the bad input.nnThis also improves the remote tests, including giving more guidance onntests that require further configuration before they'll pass.n

Braintree Blue: Return :credit_card_tokenHaving the token at the top level of the params hash when applicablenmeans much less digging around in the internals of how Braintreenstructures their results.n

Braintree Blue: Allow unstoring just a credit cardUnfortunately the Braintree implementation of store/unstore/update wasnoriginally made very customer-centric where ActiveMerchant is creditncard centric. This means that #unstore expects a customer id rather thanna credit card token. To at least allow unstoring a card only, thisnallows passing a credit card token for removal; the customer id must benpassed as nil for it to work, though.n
Braintree Blue: Add cards to existing customersWhen calling #store with an explicit customer id it's useful to add thencard to the customer with the id if it exists vs. dying with an error.n

Bogus: Add Check supportProvides support for passing valid and invalid account numbers to thenbogus gateway and returning relevant error messages.nnA valid account number is any account number that ends with 1.nAn invalid account number is any account number that ends with 2.nnAny object that responds to `account_number` will be treated as a check.nnNote, because ActiveMerchant::Billing::Check has a `number` attributenin addition to `account_number`, priority is given to `number` fornbackwards compatibility.nnCREDIT_ERROR_MESSAGE was removed because it was the same asnERROR_MESSAGE.nnCloses #944.n

This means that if you perform an operation with a card URInand an email address, you get a Funding instrument is not associatednwith account message, along with an error from Balanced.nnBy always associating the card to the (created) account if you're notngiven an `account_uri`, you can avoid this issue and are able to usenbalanced.js with the BalancedGateway.nnCloses #992.n

Quickpay: Fix passing acquirers fieldThe original implementation of protocol v7 called this field acquirern(without the s), which matched old and incorrect documentationnprovided in the past by Quickpay. We learned via Quickpaynsupport (through debug of a chargify.com merchant issue) that the fieldnin the request is called acquirers, representing a list of acquirersnto attempt, ordered by preference (i.e. `acquirers=nets,teller`).  Thenresponse will contain a field called acquirer which conveys whichnacquirer was actually used in the transaction.nnThe correct documentation can now be found on the Quickpay website:nhttp://doc.quickpay.net/api/messagetypes.html#index1h2nhttp://doc.quickpay.net/api/messagetypes.html#index2h2nnBefore this change, attempting to set the old `:acquirer` option wouldnresult in an MD5check hash mismatch, since the ActiveMerchant code wouldnuse the `acquirer` field in the calculation, but Quickpay would usen`acquirers`.nnAfter this change, both ActiveMerchant and Quickpay agree on thenMD5check hash when the `:acquirers` option is set, and the `:acquirers`noption has the intended effect of setting the preferred acquirers fornthe transaction. (The latter can be negative-tested by setting thenvalue for acquirers to an invalid acquirer value and observing thenerror response: Error in field: acquirers)nnDespite the change to the option key (`acquirer` to `acquirers`), I feelnthis is a safe, backwards compatible change since attempting to set thenold option could never result in a successful transaction - the MD5checknhash mismatch error would always occur.nnNote: I asked Quickpay to update all of their v7 documentation tonreflect the correct field name.  At this time it appears they havendone so.nnCloses #1246.n

Authorize.Net CIM: Fix updating a payment profileIn order to use the same card number when updating a payment profile (anpartial update), you must send the last-four digits of the card as thenCreditCard#number, masked (e.g. `XXXX11234`).nnThis change checks if the card number being passed inton`add_credit_card` is 4 digits. If it is, we assume a partial update isnbeing attempted, and we mask this value in the way Auth.Net expects.nnSee http://www.authorize.net/support/CIM_XML_guide.pdf, page 70, undern`cardNumber`.n

Wirecard: Add store/purchase/authorize by refWirecard supports the notion of Recurring Transactions by allowingnthe merchant to provide a reference to an earlier transactionn(the GuWID) rather than a credit card.  A reusable reference (GuWID)ncan be obtained by sending a purchase or authorization transactionnwith the element RECURRING_TRANSACTION/Type set to Initial.nSubsequent transactions can then use the GuWID in place of a creditncard by setting RECURRING_TRANSACTION/Type to Repeated.nnThis implementation of card store utilizes a Wirecard AuthorizationnCheck (a Preauthorization that is automatically reversed).nIt defaults to a check amount of 100 (i.e. $1.00) but this can benoverriden.  In order to reuse the stored reference, then+authorization+ from the response should be saved by applicationncode.nnAlready present was the ability to run a purchase transaction usingna GuWID.  This commit adds the ability to do the same for annauthorization transaction.nnNote: any transaction can generate a reusable GuWID reference bynsetting the option :recurring to Initial.  This functionalitynalready existed but is now documented.nnCloses #1243.n

Allow ignoring any MultiResponse sub-responseThis enables use (for instance) to void an authorize when verifying ancard without a failure of the void causing the verify to fail.n

Stripe: Add ability to verify a cardFor Stripe, a verification is an `authorization` followed by a `void` ofnthat authorization.nnThe minimum authorization Stripe allows is 50 cents so we use that.nnRelevant docs:nhttps://stripe.com/docs/api#create_chargennWe're now taking advantage of the ability of a MultiResponse to ignorenthe result of some of the responses.  In this case, we don't want then`verify` to fail if the `void` fails.  The important part is then`authorize`.nnCloses #1279.n

Paypal: Add ability to verify a cardPaypal supports zero dollar authorizations, but only for mastercard andnvisa.  Relevant docs:nnhttps://developer.paypal.com/docs/classic/paypal-payments-pro/integration-guide/WPDPGettingStarted/#cardverificationsnnTo verify a card, we do a zero dollar `auth` if it's mastercard or visa.nOtherwise, we do a $1 `auth` followed by a `void`.nnWe take advantage of the new ability in MultiResponse to ignore thenresults of parts of the response.  In this case, if the void fails, wendon't care.nnCloses #1280.n

Authorize.net: Add ability to verify a cardI see some discussion out there on the interwebs around Authorize.netnsupporting $0 authorizations for Visa only but it looks like support fornit is dependent on the merchant account sitting behind the gatewaynaccount.nnTo make `verify` work for all authorize.net accounts, it's implementednas a $1.00 `auth` followed by a `void`.nnCloses #1281.n

Braintree: Add ability to verify a cardIt looks like Braintree has some support for zero dollar authorizations:nnhttps://support.braintreepayments.com/customer/portal/articles/1429320-card-verificationnnHowever, the feature depends on the card type and is hampered by thenfact that some underlying processors don't support it.  Braintreenaccommodates this by attempting a zero dollar `auth` and if that failsnthey then attempt a $1 `auth`.nnWe're going to stick with a simpler approach.  Do a $1 `auth` and then an`void`.  It'll always work, and it's only one `auth` API call.nnThis adds `verify` to both Braintree Blue and Braintree Orange.  Addednbonus is that Transax gets it too since it shares behavior withnBraintree Orange.nnRemote tests are working across the board.  I didn't add unit tests fornBraintree Blue because those unit tests are somewhat off the beaten pathnthan our unit tests for other gateways due to the fact that we're usingnthe Braintree gem.  The unit tests there aren't the easiest to mock out.nI suspect we're relying on the remote tests for Braintree Blue in thencases where the unit tests are deficient.  Long term, I suspect we'dnlike to move away from using the gem, but I'm not sure how feasible thatnis at this point.nnCloses #1282.n

Enhance gateway generator to support verifyWe now support the verify operation in a few gateways and we'llnbe gradually adding support in others over time.  This commit helps thenoperation get implemented in new gateways as they're added.nnCloses #1283.n

Redsys: Improve handling of order_idPreviously, we were raising an ArgumentError if the order_id didn'tncomply with Redsys order_id formatting rules.  Now we try to clean it upnthe best we can and we no longer raise the ArgumentError.nnThe motivation for this is pretty straightforward.  Most gateways arenpretty lenient about the formatting of fields like description,norder_id, etc.  Users of Active Merchant pass these fields to multiplengateway types and they don't expect an exception to be raised if a valuendoesn't comply with a given gateway's particular rules in terms of size,nformat, etc.nnI wish I could claim credit for how we're cleaning up the order_id tonaccount for the quite particular rules Redsys has around this field.nThe truth is that @ntalbott is the mastermind behind the simplenmechanism we're using.n

AuthorizeNet: Prevent test mode using live gatewayAuthorize.net allows one to switch their production gateway account intonTest Mode.  If the account is in Test Mode, the response will includenn<testRequest>1</testRequest>nnDocs for it:nnhttp://developer.authorize.net/api/reference/#payment-transactions-charge-a-credit-cardnnIf the gateway instance you're dealing with is connecting to thentest_url, it matters not.  But if you're working with a live gatewaynconnecting to the live_url and you get back a response indicating thatnthe gateway backend is actually in Test Mode, then that's a seriousnissue and the transaction should fail.  We don't want customers thinkingnthey're collecting real money when in fact they're not.n

Stripe: Make version explicitStripe has many API versions, some of which are breaking changes:nnhttps://stripe.com/docs/upgrades#api-changelognnIf someone today created a new Stripe account, the remote tests wouldnnot pass because Stripe has changed some of the attribute responses aroundn`cards` (used by our `store` method):nnhttps://stripe.com/docs/upgrades#2015-02-18nnIn addition, the `statement_description` no longer works since it's beennreplaced by `statement_descriptor`.  Clients of Active Merchant may benusing `statement_description` so we're now mapping that ton`statement_descriptor` under the covers.nnSo how do we solve these issues?  This commit makes the specification ofnthe Stripe API version explicit in the headers.  Previously, you couldnspecify the version you wanted to use for a particular transaction.  Or,nyou could specify it when you instantiated the gateway.  In this commit,nwe still allow such customizations.  If no version is specified though,nwe explicitly use the current latest version (2015-04-07).nnThis improves things such that if Stripe releases a new, breaking APInversion, clients using Active Merchant won't be broken.  If we want tonupgrade to the default version Active Merchant uses, we can do sonexplicitly and change the underlying options we're passing accordingly.nnIf you're already specifying the Stripe API version, then this commitnshouldn't break you.  If you're relying on the default API version ofnthe underlying Stripe account, there may be issues which we'll fix as wenlearn of them.nnCloses #1678.n

NMI gateway (non-Auth.net mode) supportThis is a rewrite of the NMI adapter to support their native API and notnthe previous Auth.net emulation mode API. Every attempt has been made tonretain backwards compatibility. However, there may be small discrepanciesndepending on your usage of the API.nnWhat is known is that there are a few fields without a sensible mappingnto the new API. These request params include:nn* cardholder_authentication_value and authentication_indicator which arenthird party 3D Secure authentication fields. The NMI adapter doesn'tnyet support these fields in its native API.n* solution_id (application_id), which identifies the agent making the APIncall, has no equal in the native API.nnAlso, the native API does not support the notion of a fraud_review, so thatnfunctionality is not available in the rewritten implementation.nnThe advantages of using the NMI native API include being on the mostncurrent version which will make future development easier, as well asnsupport for features such as ACH/echeck payment methods (which thisnrewrite does include).n

Stripe: Allow custom zero decimal currenciesThe Stripe adapter has been overriding which currencies are zero decimalncurrencies for awhile.  The parent Gateway class defines a default listnbut Stripe has its own list:nnhttps://support.stripe.com/questions/which-zero-decimal-currencies-does-stripe-supportnnThe ability to override was broken in this commit:nhttps://github.com/activemerchant/active_merchant/commit/2a35543b4a8348cd115f4b2f138731e5f3c4a080nnsince the `non_fractional_currency?` method was changed to a classnmethod.nnThis commit allows us to override it again.  It also adds the VNDncurrency to Stripe's list since they now list that currency in theirndocs.nnCloses #1920.n

TWD isn't a zero decimal currencyIt was made a zero decimal currency in this commit:nhttps://github.com/activemerchant/active_merchant/commit/1d36d156ff3ec8b556082b3cf4566080769fc7d8nnThis was likely primarily for Paypal Express which _does_ list it as anzero dollar currency:nnhttps://developer.paypal.com/webapps/developer/docs/classic/api/currency_codes/nnIt's _not_ listed as a zero decimal currency in the ISO reference XML:nnhttp://www.currency-iso.org/en/home/tables/table-a1.htmlnnAnd Stripe has confirmed that it's not a zero decimal currency.nnAll that to say that by default, a Gateway that uses `localized_amount`nwill no longer treat TWD as a zero decimal currency.  Our Paypal Expressnadapter now specifies a custom list of zero decimal currencies that's innline with their docs.n

FirstDataE4: Fix void for even dollar transactionsIn 7e0508bcce8b76043c187851730480d7c2e272e3, void was fixed when thenamount of the auth was something like 29234 and `to_i` was giving annamount that didn't match.  In that commit, we debated using `round` ornjust removing the decimal point to avoid weird rounding errors.  What wendidn't realize was that when the amount is 5000 ($50.00), the gatewaynreturns back 50.0 in the response rather than 50.00.  So simply removingnthe decimal point doesn't work in that case since the amounts won'tnmatch.nnThis commit switches to `round` which may end up working all of thentime.  If it turns out to not work in some cases, we may end up takingna different approach such as passing through the initial amount of thenauth all the way through to the `commit` method such that it can benremembered rather than relying on the gateway's response bodynamount.n

Removing codes AN and KV from the countries list and SecurionPayGateway as they are not part of the ActiveMerchant-selected standard ISO-3166-1.AN is a deleted code from a different standard ISO 3166-2. It doesn't refer to a country but to the country-subdivision Netherlands Antilles.nnKV appears to refer to Kosovo. Kosovo is a disputed territory not recognized by ISO 3166-1. The code XK is being used by several organizations as a temporary country code for Kosovo, but it is not an accepted standard.nnBecause these codes aren't part of ISO-3166-1 and because they are only used by SecurionPay, I'm just removing them.n

Remove non ISO-3166-1 AN and KV country codesRemoving codes AN and KV from the countries list and SecurionPayGateway as theynare not part of the ActiveMerchant-selected standard ISO-3166-1.nnAN is a deleted code from a different standard ISO 3166-2. It doesn't refernto a country but to the country-subdivision Netherlands Antilles.nnKV appears to refer to Kosovo. Kosovo is a disputed territory not recognized bynISO 3166-1. The code XK is being used by several organizations as a temporaryncountry code for Kosovo, but it is not an accepted standard.nnBecause these codes aren't part of ISO-3166-1 and because they are only used bynSecurionPay, I'm just removing them.nnCloses #2092n

Worldpay: Format non-fractional currency amounts correctlyhttps://github.com/activemerchant/active_merchant/pull/2084 introduced anregression to the Worldpay gateway wherein it was no longer implementingnthe correct contract for non-fractional currencies.nnOur [base gatewayntests](https://github.com/jasonwebster/active_merchant/blob/07e28c4936c2ae46f0470d878c19f36564c3df6e/test/unit/gateways/gateway_test.rb#L83-L91)nand [Stripentests](https://github.com/jasonwebster/active_merchant/blob/07e28c4936c2ae46f0470d878c19f36564c3df6e/test/unit/gateways/stripe_test.rb#L431-L440)nfor example, which is another gateway with a `:cents` money format,nensure that you want to charge u00c2u00a5100, you actually have to pass inn`10000`, as if the non-fractional currency _was_ fractional. Remove leading or trailing whitespace from credit card nameWhen a credit card name is set using `name=` method, the first and lastnnames will be split into their respective fields. For example-nncard = ActiveMerchant::Billing::CreditCard.new name: Johnncard.first_name # => ncard.last_name # => JohnnnThe issue is if we call `name` again on the card, we get a leading space-nncard.name # =>  JohnnnThis update will remove any leading or trailing whitespaces when callingnthe name method regardless of the value of first and last name or hownit was originally set.nncard = ActiveMerchant::Billing::CreditCard.new name: Johnncard.first_name # => ncard.last_name # => Johnncard.name # => JohnnnCloses #2289n

Fix Redsys test broken due to year rolloverCurrently a redsys gateway test is failing due to its it's stubbednresponse relying on a generated signature using the current date. I'venopted to revert back to using the year `2017` explicitly because thenBase64 signature is generated using a combination of test data,nincluding date and OpenSSL cipher encrypted secret key + order.nnReverting back will also prevent this test from breaking on every yearnrollover. Alternatively we dould still rely on `Time.now.year + 1` onnthis test, but then the stubbed response would need to be updated evernyear.nnCloses https://github.com/activemerchant/active_merchant/pull/2296n

SafeCharge: Track currency from original transactionSending in a currency is required for all SafeCharge transaction types.nMoreover, SafeCharge does not keep track of the original currency usednfor an authorize or purchase so if an authorize is done using EUR andn then a subsequent capture is run on that authorization, the capturen will be done in USD instead of EUR since the adapter defaults to USD.nnOf course this could be mitigated by sending in a currency code intonthe options hash for a void/refund/capture, but it's a bit silly to neednto remember that and pass that in when you'll most likely want to runnsubsequent transaction requests (e.g. refund, void, and capture) on thensame currency.nnThis add the currency code used in the original transaction to thenauthorization response field so running a void/refund/capture willnalways do so in the original currency used vs defaulting to USD.nnCloses #2470n

Prevent frozen objects being assigned as wiredump device (#2660)The wiredump device takes an object that quacks like an IO stream (e.g. File or String) and passes it along to Net:HTTP#set_debug_output where it is used by the private `D` method for appending log messages, as seen here: https://github.com/ruby/ruby/blob/c91cb76f8d84b2963f6ede2ef445ad46a6104216/lib/net/http.rb#L1567rnrnIf the device is set to an empty string literal (i.e. ) and the frozen string literal magic comment is added to the file, this causes `RuntimeError: can't modify frozen String` exceptions. The stacktrace can be confusing since setting up the gateway object and using it usually happens in different places in the application code.rnrnThis PR aims to fail early if such a situation occurs and provide a stacktrace that clearly points to the cause of the error.

Safe Charge: Provisions adapter for 3DS purchasesSafe Charge has implemented a system by which they determine whethernpurchases should be routed through the 3DS flow or not. If the merchantnis not approved for 3DS, transactions will occur as before, outside ofnthe 3DS flow. If a merchant is approved for 3DS, Sage Charge willnevaluate the card for enrollment status. If the card is not enrolled, itnwill be processed as a 'regular' transaction. If the card is enrolled,nthe Safe Charge response will include the 'xid', 'ascurl', and then'pareq'.nnCloses #2661nnRemote Tests:n21 tests, 62 assertions, 0 failures, 0 errors, 0 pendings, 0 omissions,n0 notificationsn100% passednnUnit Tests:n17 tests, 76 assertions, 0 failures, 0 errors, 0 pendings, 0 omissions,n0 notificationsn100% passedn

Stripe: Fix Partial Application Fee RefundsPreviously, when a partial application fee refund was requested, thenconnected stripe_account option was sent in the authentication headernfor both the fee retrieval call AND the application fee refund itself.nSince the fee exists only on the main Platform account, sending thenconnected stripe_account for the refund meant it was looking in thenwrong place, and failed. Now we remove the stripe_account field beforenthe partial refund, so it is not sent in headers.nnThis also switches to a method of fetching the transaction to obtain thenid of the application fee, rather than querying all application feesnassociated with the transaction, since it simplifies things, and thenprior method did not seem to have any benefits over this (havingnmultiple application fees doesn't seem possible currently). Errornmessaging around this has been updated as well.nnThis also involved updating the aging remote_stripe_connect_tests to usenthe stripe_destination in fixtures as the stripe_account option, and tonremove assertions that are now invalid due to the changes to responsenstructure in https://stripe.com/docs/upgrades#2013-08-13nUnit tests were likewise updated for the partial fee refund methodnchanges.nnCloses #2713nnRemote (two failing likely due to unrelated stale test data):n59 tests, 253 assertions, 2 failures, 0 errors, 0 pendings, 0 omissions, 0 notificationsn96.6102% passednnRemote Connect:n3 tests, 10 assertions, 0 failures, 0 errors, 0 pendings, 0 omissions, 0 notificationsn100% passednnUnit:n122 tests, 651 assertions, 0 failures, 0 errors, 0 pendings, 0 omissions, 0 notificationsn100% passedn

Remove all TLS 1.0 version pins (#2774)Most of these were added years ago as workarounds. They were never revisited to see if gateways had fixed their SSL setup. By removing the pinned version requirement, the highest supported version will be negotiated between the client and the server.rnrnTLS 1.0 is old with known vulnerabilities that require server mitigations to be properly configured. Version 1.2 was released in 2008 and is considered secure with most cipher configurations.rnrnThe PCI DSS v3.2 disallows TLS 1.0 unless existing implementations have applied for an exception. However, this exception is not valid after June 30, 2018. I have verified (with `curl -v`) that all live and test URLs of the affected gateways support TLS 1.2.

Add logging of SSL connection detailsOn June 30 the PCI DSS mandates TLS 1.1 or better for securely transmitting payment data. This refinement to Net::HTTP allows us to get the required details within the scope of the ActiveMerchant::Connection class, without monkey patching globally.nnExample output:n```nirb(main):004:0> gw.authorize(100, test)nI, [2018-05-30T11:22:44.565084 #44620]  INFO -- : [ActiveMerchant::Billing::PayflowGateway] connection_http_method=POST connection_uri=https://payflowpro.paypal.comnI, [2018-05-30T11:22:45.165265 #44620]  INFO -- : [ActiveMerchant::Billing::PayflowGateway] connection_ssl_version=TLSv1.2 connection_ssl_cipher=ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256n```n

To grandfather in our existing code, I'venpre-generated a `.rubocop_todo.yml` file, which will allowngradual migration.nnTo run RuboCop, you can run `rake rubocop`, but I've also introduced antest:local Rake target that runs both the unit tests and RuboCopnchecks. Decide CC brand by lambda, not regexPreviously, we were using pure regexes to determine a credit card brandnbased on its BIN. The problem is that you can't reliably determinenBINs based on regexes: Maestro overlaps with MasterCard, Electron justnhas a pile of buckets, and so on.nnAs a first step, remove any reliance on raw regexes, and instead switchnto using lambdas. For now, this is functionally equivalent, but willnallow more precise brand determination in a follow-up commit.nnUnit: 3927 tests, 68196 assertions, 0 failures, 0 errors, 0 pendings, 2 omissions, 0 notificationsn100% passedn

Remove support for LaserLaser has been shuttered since 2014, and its BIN ranges overlap withnmdoern Maestro and MasterCard ranges. In prep for fixing up thosenranges, remove support for Laser entirely.n

Fix Maestro and MasterCard detectionThere are two pieces to this. First, some of the old Maestro rangenis simply wrong at this point (the 50 BIN appears dead), so remove testsnfor those ranges and alter the detection not to pick them up. Secondly,nas continuing prep for adding new card types and handling BIN detectionnbetter, convert both MasterCard and Maestro over to proper rangendetection, rather than some overly exciting regexes.nnSource: https://www.mastercard.us/content/dam/mccom/global/documents/mastercard-rules.pdf,npage 73.nnUnit: 3926 tests, 68184 assertions, 0 failures, 0 errors, 0 pendings, 2 omissions, 0 notificationsn100% passedn

Remove the upperbound constraint on ActiveSupport: (#3065)- During every ActiveSupport major bump, this gemspec needs to be updated,rn  I think we are being too conservative and having an upperbound limitrn  doesn't help.rnrn  If we wanted to be really conservative we would have to add arn  upperbound constraint on the minor version as well (`< 5.x`) sincern  Rails doesn't follow semver and minor version can introduce breakingrn  changes.rnrn  What I think is better is to remove the upperbound constraint,rn  and test AM directly on ActiveSupport edge.rn  Looking at the commit rates on this project, CI would runrn  largely enough to cover us. But we can also add another safety netrn  and run travis on a schedule.

Worldpay: Introduce normalized stored credential optionsThe Visa/Mastercard Stored Credentials Framework is becoming standardnfunctionality across all gateways. There are a few gateways in ActivenMerchant which support sending in very specific fields in the optionsnhash which will be set while building a auth/purchase request. HowevernActive Merchant should be a consistent interface to gateways and to thatnend, this commit is introducing a new normalized hash which containsna standard set of fields by which the proper logic should be able tonconstruct a correct stored credentials request to any gateway.nThe hash takes the following structure:nn{n  stored_credential: {ninital_transaction: Boolean, # either true or falsenrecurring: Boolean, # either true or falseninitiator: String, # either merchant or cardholdernnetwork_transaction_id: String # returned card network transaction idn  }n}nnWith those 4 bits of information, you should be able to successfully addnthe necessary fields to any gateway request. Note that there should benlogic to add the necessary values in the request (see this commit as annexample) and not all gateways will need or accept all those fields.nnIn many ways this is similar to normalizing address fields in thatnActive Merchant always expects and address hash to use a field `zip`ninstead of something like `postalCode`. However the downside to thisnsetup is that there is no field level validation which we get withnsomething like an Active Merchant CreditCard.nnLastly, this commit also allows for the specific fields to also be sentnto maintain backwards compatibility with anyone who might already benusing the specific fields.n

Worldpay: Adjust use of normalized stored credentials hashPreviously the new/beta normalized stored credential hash was using anboolean value to indicate if a transaction was part of a recurringntransaction or not. However, this did not allow for the case of gatewaysn(like Worldpay) to take into account transactions that are part of anninstallment. This adjusts the previously recurring field to use thenname transaction_type which accepts a string of either:nn- installmentn- recurringn- unschedulednnThis should allow more flexibility to for other gateways that also haventhe notion of a payment that is part of an installment.nnNote that this normalized hash is still in beta use. The hashnstructure itself may change and until there is solid use around itnacross multiple gateways, it will likely be a defined-yet-not-enforcednhash rather than an object which provides guarantees around fieldnvalues.nnCloses #3139n

Issue the actual refund against the chargern2. Fetch the charge to get the application fee identifierrn3. Issue the application fee refund against the original application feernrnCurrently, if either 2 or 3 fail while 1 succeeds, the `#refund`rnmethod's response is a failure, which is not true. This process is notrntransactional. The refund had succeeded and is not rolled back, whichrnisn't possible to do anyway.

Adyen: Add normalized hash of 3DS 2.0 data fields from web browsersIn an effort to begin supporting the intiation of 3DS 2.0 transactions,nthis introduces another normalized hash for web browser data that can benmapped to the fields a gateway is expecting. Similarly to storedncredentials, this hash should be used across all gateways in which 3DSn2.0 browser data is meant to be submitted so there is a single interfacenfor the client/device data.nnEventually I suspect this hash should also support mobile app informationnby changing out the channel field and doing additional logic around that,nbut for now we're starting with web browsers only.nnThe structure of the hash is as follows:nnthree_ds_2: {n  channel: browser,n  browser_info: {naccept_header: unknown,ndepth: 100,njava: false,nlanguage: US,nheight: 1000,nwidth: 500,ntimezone: -120,nuser_agent: unknownn  }n}nnThis should be all of the data gateways are expecting, however as withnall payment gateways I imagine there are some that will accept ornrequire additional data. In those cases I suspect we can add that datanto this additional hash for a specific gateways needs.n

VISA's stored credential transaction framework does not support 'recurring' nor 'installment' transactionsn   for cardholder-initiated, thus passing the 'cardholder' option will default 'a9' to '9' (Unscheduled Card-on-Filen   transactions initiated by the cardholder).nn2. making the change to this auth+ capture card present flow as the following to restore non-auto capture behaviour stripe was providing before its 2018-07-31 release. the change is the following:1. capture set to false for authorization (param value change)n2. update the existing charge with card data (same as current flow)n3. capture by posting to the capturen endpoint https://stripe.com/docs/api/charges/capture (completely newn step)nnnote the third step above is the new step introduced in this PR tonproperly catpure a non-auto capture charge. this means for each non-autoncapture scenario, we are making an additional network call to stripe.nnthis flow is recommended by stripe's engineer Dan Cobb:n 1. Create the charge with emv_auth_data and capture set to falsen2. Update the charge with emv_approval_datan3. Capture the charge.nn we had also tested our change in the PR through generating auth+capturen charges successfully.nnwe expect this change will ensure that authorizations aren'tnautomatcally captured for the UK and IE API consumers to maintain the behaviour before stripe's api change in 2018-07-31 release, with one additional network call to stripe.n

Quickbooks: Add OAuth 2.0 support, support voidQuickbooks is deprecating OAuth 1.0 support, and requiring OAuthn2.0 no later than December 17, 2019. This PR adds support fornOAuth 2.0, requiring the access_token, refresh_token, client_idnand client_secret when creating a gateway. When refresh_token isnpresent, OAuth 2.0 authentication will be attempted. If notnincluded, OAuth 1.0 will be attempted and should still work untilnthe deprecation date.nnIn the Quickbooks implementation, the access_token expires everyn60 minutes and you must use the refresh_token to generate a newnone. There's no way to proactively check if the token is stillnvalid; you'll just see that the request fails with ann`AuthenticationFailed` error. This PR adds logic to each action toncheck for this error, and attempt to refresh the token and reissuenthe request when it happens.nnThis gateway also did not previously implement the void method;nsupport is added here. It required a change to authorization_fromnmethod to include the request-id since that is needed in the voidnrequest. The authorization value is split appropriately to parse outnthe value needed for a given method.nnRemote:n14 tests, 37 assertions, 0 failures, 0 errors, 0 pendings, 0 omissions, 0 notificationsn100% passednnUnit:n21 tests, 114 assertions, 0 failures, 0 errors, 0 pendings, 0 omissions, 0 notificationsn100% passedn

Adyen: Allow the use of the storeToken endpoint for storeThe store action currently uses the /authorise endpoint when executingnthe store call. While Adyen does return the recurringDetailReference innthe authorize response, there are some drawbacks to using this endpointnif you are looking for a pure tokenize call to store payment details atnAdyen with no additional side effects.nn1. The /authorise endpoint will run a full authorization at the issuingnbank meaning the authorize request itself could fail preventing a fullntokenize at Adyen despite there being nothing inherently wrong with thencard itself.nn2. It's possible for a response from the authorize call to respond withna 3DS flow which would be suboptimal if you're not interested in doingnthat at the particular time of storing the card.nnThis PR is meant to be a starting point for iteration on adding supportnfor the use of storeToken. As always there are always backwardsncompatibility considerations and ensuring that both forms ofntokenizing at Adyen can work together seamlessly. My hope is that thisngives a good foundation with a real remote test for introspecting andndetermining a best path forward.nnAs a side note: storeToken is only available if a specific role is addednto your user in Adyen so it's not universally available out of the box.nnA couple notes about this particular implementation:nn* Because this is a feature Adyen switches on a per account basis, it'snopt-in with the default being the current implementation then the addednability to pass in a new option for using /storeToken instead.nn* The url building had to be altered a bit since there's no version innthe URL for storeToken AND it's a different sub resource (Recurring)nn* I tried to ensure there was backwards compatibility will all othernactions by only appending new checks. But I think this needs an extranclose look.nn* There are 2 failing remote tests around 3DS that I don't believe arenrelated to this in any way. But worth a second set of eyes.n
